1
00:00:00,110 --> 00:00:06,170
In this video we are going to learn integration events, how domain event leads to integration events

2
00:00:06,170 --> 00:00:11,540
and transition from the domain to integration event, and the difference between domain and integration

3
00:00:11,540 --> 00:00:12,230
events.

4
00:00:12,500 --> 00:00:17,510
At the core, they are the same thing, a representation of something that happened in the past.

5
00:00:17,510 --> 00:00:22,640
However, their purpose, use case and implementation details are different.

6
00:00:22,640 --> 00:00:23,540
Let me see.

7
00:00:23,570 --> 00:00:24,380
Domain events.

8
00:00:24,380 --> 00:00:28,100
Domain events published and consumed within a single domain.

9
00:00:28,100 --> 00:00:32,030
So you publish and subscribe to the event in the same application instance.

10
00:00:32,030 --> 00:00:36,200
They are strictly within the boundary of the microservice or domain context.

11
00:00:36,200 --> 00:00:42,410
They typically indicate something that happened within the aggregate and domain events happen in process

12
00:00:42,410 --> 00:00:45,860
and synchronously sent using in-memory message pass.

13
00:00:45,860 --> 00:00:48,860
As an example, we can give order created event.

14
00:00:48,860 --> 00:00:54,980
So if you look at the integration event integration events used to communicate state changes or events

15
00:00:54,980 --> 00:01:01,010
between different bounded contexts or microservices, they are more about the overall systems reaction

16
00:01:01,010 --> 00:01:02,630
to certain domain events.

17
00:01:02,630 --> 00:01:07,700
Integration events should be asynchronously sent with a message broker over a queue.

18
00:01:07,790 --> 00:01:11,540
Integration events are consumed by other subsystems.

19
00:01:11,570 --> 00:01:17,330
As an example, after handling the order created event, an order created integration event might be

20
00:01:17,330 --> 00:01:23,000
published to the message broker like the RabbitMQ, which could then be consumed by other microservices.

21
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:28,790
So if you compare with the domain and integration event, we can say that domain events happen in process

22
00:01:28,790 --> 00:01:29,810
and synchronously.

23
00:01:29,810 --> 00:01:35,450
On the other hand, the integration event should be asynchronously domain events published and consumed

24
00:01:35,450 --> 00:01:36,650
within a single domain.

25
00:01:36,650 --> 00:01:40,460
So you publish and subscribe to events in the same application instance.

26
00:01:40,460 --> 00:01:44,870
On the other hand, integration events are consumed by other subsystems.

27
00:01:44,870 --> 00:01:50,390
Domain events are sent using in-memory message pass, and integration events are sent with a message

28
00:01:50,390 --> 00:01:51,620
broker over a queue.

29
00:01:52,220 --> 00:01:53,390
So let's see.

30
00:01:53,390 --> 00:01:57,050
Each of microservices has domain and integration events.

31
00:01:57,050 --> 00:02:02,060
So we will develop initially microservices that include domain and integration events.

32
00:02:02,060 --> 00:02:05,270
And the first one is basket checkout integration event.

33
00:02:05,270 --> 00:02:10,610
So basket checkout is an integration event that published from the basket microservices to RabbitMQ

34
00:02:10,610 --> 00:02:13,100
and consume from the ordering microservices.

35
00:02:13,100 --> 00:02:18,800
So we will develop basket checkout event during this section and basket checkout integration event that

36
00:02:18,800 --> 00:02:24,290
will subscribe and consume by the ordering microservices from the RabbitMQ using the mass transit in

37
00:02:24,290 --> 00:02:27,410
order to perform asynchronous event driven communication.

38
00:02:27,590 --> 00:02:34,580
So in the second domain event, we can say that order created domain event and in ordering when consumes

39
00:02:34,580 --> 00:02:39,650
the basket checkout integration event into handler class, it will create a new order into ordering

40
00:02:39,650 --> 00:02:40,640
microservices.

41
00:02:40,640 --> 00:02:46,730
So in ordering microservices, when a new order is created, it will raise an order, created domain

42
00:02:46,730 --> 00:02:49,460
event and triggers internal operations.

43
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:55,400
And after that we can give order created integration event for the order fulfillment operations.

44
00:02:55,400 --> 00:03:01,130
So when dispatching the order created domain event, a domain event handler class will publish an order

45
00:03:01,130 --> 00:03:06,530
created integration event for the order fulfillment, microservices and implementing Saga pattern.

46
00:03:06,530 --> 00:03:10,010
So this is the transition from the domain to integration event.

47
00:03:10,010 --> 00:03:15,290
Once the order created domain event is handled and order created, integration event is published.

48
00:03:15,290 --> 00:03:21,110
So this integration event can be used to implement complex workflows like a Saga pattern involving the

49
00:03:21,110 --> 00:03:22,250
other microservices.

50
00:03:22,250 --> 00:03:26,630
So here you can see the domain and integration events that we are going to create.

51
00:03:26,630 --> 00:03:32,060
This is the end to end process of the domain and integration events for each of microservices.

52
00:03:32,060 --> 00:03:38,120
And the process starts from the basket microservices that publish the basket checkout integration event.

53
00:03:38,120 --> 00:03:43,670
And this will be consumed by the ordering microservices and handling the ordering microservices.

54
00:03:43,670 --> 00:03:50,240
And when ordering microservices consume these integration event, it will create a new order and this

55
00:03:50,240 --> 00:03:53,750
operation will raise an order created domain event.

56
00:03:53,750 --> 00:03:59,750
And after that this domain event dispatch and handles in the domain handler classes of the ordering

57
00:03:59,750 --> 00:04:06,290
microservices that will also lead any integration event which is the order created integration event

58
00:04:06,290 --> 00:04:09,740
and this will be performed order fulfillment use case.

59
00:04:09,740 --> 00:04:16,670
And this will be subscribing from the other microservices including the shipment, payment and notification

60
00:04:16,670 --> 00:04:20,450
to performing end to end flow of the order fulfillment process.

61
00:04:20,450 --> 00:04:25,790
So now we are at this point when we are consuming these basket checkout integration event in the order

62
00:04:25,790 --> 00:04:31,250
microservices, that we will create a new order, and this will be raised at a domain event that lead

63
00:04:31,250 --> 00:04:32,210
to integration event.

